return to the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
congressional Democrats Keith Ellison and John Lewis have tabled a bill to establish the organization of unions as a civil right .
&quot; as unions die , middle class jobs also die , &quot; said Ellison , a Democrat from Minnesota and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress .
I am therefore proud , together with the civil rights activist John Lewis , to present the Staff Authorisation Act .
this groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate on grounds of the organisation of trade unions as in other forms of discrimination - and stops such anti @-@ union forces .
the addition of the National Labour Law Act to create a way of discriminating against workers to organise a union representation to bring justice before a civil court - and to obtain compensation or penalties - is a meaningful and necessary initiative .
but it is certainly not a radical initiative - certainly not according to American standards .
indeed , the best way to understand what Ellison , Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to connect back to a very American idea .
despite the setbacks that unions have faced in recent years - in Wisconsin , Michigan and other states across the country - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to recognise , expand and respect labor rights .
there was a time when millions of Americans remember when this country called democracy , freedom of speech , freedom of the press and the right of association in a breath .
when the United States occupied Japan after World War II , General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to adopt a constitution that should ensure that militarized autocracy would replace Hedki Tojos with democracy .
fully aware that workers and their unions took a role in creating a new Japan , they used a language that explicitly acknowledged that &quot; workers &apos; rights to union and joint bargaining and action are guaranteed . &quot;
when the United States occupy Germany after World War II , General Dwight urged David Eisenhower and his staff to write a constitution that would ensure fascism would replace Adolf Hitler with strong democracy .
in recognition of the fact that workers would have to organise themselves and raise their voices in the new nation , Germans inserted a clause explicitly saying : &quot; the right to set up associations to safeguard and improve the working and economic conditions is guaranteed to each individual and every profession or business .
agreements that restrict this right or aim to diminish it are null and void ; these measures are illegal .
when former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Human Rights Commission , which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights , as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global agreement , Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that &quot; everyone has the right to form unions to protect their interests . &quot;
for generations , Americans have accepted the basic premise that labour rights are human rights .
when this country discussed how to form civil and democratic societies , Americans said that the right to create a union - and that this union should then participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government offices - should be protected .
after these rights came under fire in America , it is indeed very wise to revisit the American ideal , which means that the working population must have the right to unite and to make their voice heard in a free and open society .
as Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago :
the story is a great teacher .
now everyone knows that the labor movement did not restrict the nation &apos;s strength , but enlarged it .
by raising the standard of living of millions of people , work has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production .
those who attack the work forget these simple truths , but history keeps them .
history remembers , and we should do so .
formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as a protection against discrimination in the creation of employee representation - is long overdue .
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past , triggering the promise of democracy .
judge halts temporary law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to shut down
a US federal judge on Sunday provisionally halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana , from which lawyers say it probably led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state .
this measure , which was elevated to law by Bobby Jindal , governor of Louisiana , in June and is due to enter into force on Sept . 1 , would force doctors who conduct abortions to acquire a patient &apos;s right to take part in a hospital within a radius of 30 miles around their practice .
however , the judge &apos;s decision means that doctors may , for the time being , continue to have legal abortions while requesting such a right .
&quot; the plaintiffs can continue to work law while seeking to obtain these rights , &quot; federal judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling .
a hearing will be held within one month for the judge to reach a more permanent decision on the law .
abortion advocates welcomed the decision , the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures and said doctors were daring so more time to gain hospital registration rights .
&quot; today &apos;s decision means that women in Louisiana are escaping a back @-@ to @-@ back law that wants to take them their health and rights , &quot; said Nancy Northup , president and chairman of the Center for Reproductive Rights , which had sued on behalf of three of the state &apos;s five clinics to halt the law .
it was not immediately clear whether the ruling also extended to doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the lawsuit and also requested referral rights .
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws , with courts recently declaring such measures in Alabama and Mississippi unconstitutional .
key points of a law in Texas that would have forced most of the clinics remaining in the state to shut down were stopped by a federal judge on Friday .
abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists , as well as the American Medical Association , agree that enrollment rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors .
abortion opponents maintain that the measures serve to protect women &apos;s health , although some also welcomed the impact of closing clinics .
only one doctor conducting abortions in Louisiana has patient consent rights , the Center for Reproductive Rights said .
if all the other doctors in the state are forced to no longer perform abortions , that doctor , fearing for his safety , would no longer perform the operation , the group said .
in their argument against the ruling , representatives of the state of Louisiana said they would not punish doctors for carrying out abortions , while their applications for patient consent would still be pending .
delayed diagnoses and lack of access to the best treatments lead to higher death rates from ovarian cancer in rural areas .
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have posted a video footage for their mother online , who died of ovarian cancer in 2007 .
for women in rural Australia , there is a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than for women in cities .
researchers analyzed the medical data of more than 1100 Australians who found ovarian cancer in 2005 and found that only 25 percent five years after diagnosis were still alive .
research director Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Medical Research Institute said that for those living in rural and remote regions of the state , mortality risk during the study was 20 percent higher than for those in urban areas .
small STUDIE : new medicines could slow lung and ovarian cancer
researchers looked at women &apos;s medical care over seven years .
Dr Jordan said that the age of a woman in diagnosis , the type of ovarian cancer , existing pre @-@ disease and social and economic status also influenced survival opportunities .
for older women and those whose cancer was already advanced at the diagnosis stage , the survival rate was lowest .
for those living in rural and remote regions of the state , mortality risk during the study was 20 percent higher than for those in urban areas .
although the study did not investigate why outside the city , living women with greater likelihood of ovarian cancer died , Dr Jordan suspects a delayed diagnosis and lack of access to the best treatment centers as possible factors .
&quot; this disease is best treated by gynaecological oncologists , and these are mostly found in larger cities , &quot; she said .
despite improving telemedicine services to counter the distances , it proposed , as a possible remedy , a strengthening of the service of flown doctors to allow specialists to supply women more densely to their place of residence , as well as treatment programs for people outside their region .
Dr Jordan said that , regardless of geographical status , the study showed a poor long @-@ term survival rate among women in ovarian cancer and underlined the need for better treatment and screening strategies .
the study , funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer , is published today in the Medical Journal of Australia .
in March 2013 , Elisha Neave , a young mother of 33 years from the Gold Coast , learned that she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer .
garden centers regret falling homeowners &apos; pay
the decline , along with an increased sinking of the number of homeowners under 35 , could result in garden centers losing tens of thousands of pounds a year when today &apos;s young consumers reach the &quot; core age group for garden products , &quot; according to a study by HTA , as reported in the Financial Times .
the report says tenants spend an average of 55 percent of the amount spent by people with home for their garden .
the rise in people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens , the popular procedure to asphale pre @-@ kindergarten for parking purposes , and the falling garden size are other factors threatening the industry , in which an estimated £ 5 billion per year is implemented on sale .
in London , where over a 6 @-@ year period the share of homeowners has fallen from 61 to 43 percent , the lowest spending on garden products per household is reported .
the HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society point out that living for rent or small gardens does not mean people can &apos;t pull plants .
guy Barter , chief gardener for the RHS said : &quot; container gardeners , for example , are very popular with tenants because they can take their plants in a move . &quot;
the HTA report identified the period between 1997 and 2005 as the &quot; golden age &quot; of gardening retailers because of rising homeownership and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid @-@ 1990s .
he also forecast an improved market situation this year because of better weather following unfriendly weather conditions in March and April last year .
