Israeli children return to their schools after the war in Gaza
thousands of Israeli children from the areas near Gaza returned to schools on Monday after spending the summer in air shelters , while rocket and mortar fire went down on their communities during the 50 @-@ day war between Israel and Hamas and closed schools in Gaza while the area was recovering from fighting .
the school launch brought a sense of joy and expectation to the communities marked by rocket launchers in southern Israel , but the signs of fighting are still fresh .
in the southern city of Ashdod , staff from the Pashosh nursery , which was hit by a rocket , removed from the walls and shale walls before the students &apos; arrival .
&quot; we &apos;re a bit afraid , but are excited , &quot; said Ronit Bart , resident in the Kibbutz Saad and there English teacher .
many children from our area urgently need to return to a routine .
her 11 @-@ year @-@ old daughter Shani Bart said it feels &quot; a bit weird &quot; to suddenly go back to school .
&quot; these were difficult times , and we didn &apos;t go out of the house at all , &quot; she said .
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz near the border with Gaza to offer his support .
until a cease @-@ fire broke the war last week , thousands of residents of border communities such as Saad stayed in their homes or left their homes to move further away from Gaza and escape the missile and mortar fire .
many residents of Nahal Oz , a community near the border with Gaza in which a 4 @-@ year @-@ old boy was killed by a Palestinian mortar grenade , are still reluctant to return .
the Education Department said about a dozen families have not yet returned .
their children were provisionally housed in other schools .
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu attended a school in Sderot , a border town on Gaza that is hard to draw from the Palestinian shelling .
he appealed to the children to learn a lot and said &quot; we will make sure their knowledge works and provide you with security . &quot;
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite cease @-@ fire last Tuesday .
the ceasefire caused an immediate end to the fighting , but major problems remain unresolved , such as Hamas &apos;s call for the lifting of Gaza &apos;s Israeli @-@ Egyptian blockade and the reopening of air and seaports in Gaza .
Israel calls for Hamas to disarm and hand over the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the fighting .
a new round of indirect talks is expected to begin in Egypt later this month .
more than 2,100 Palestinians were killed in the war , three @-@ quarters of them civilians , and at least 494 children , according to estimates by the Palestinians and the UN .
Israel denies this information and estimates that at least half of those killed are fighters , but did not provide any specific evidence of this information .
on the Israeli side , 66 soldiers and six civilians , including a Thai worker , were killed .
Hamas and other militants in Gaza fired 4,591 rockets and mortar grenades during fighting on Israeli cities , most in the south of the country .
meanwhile , the Israeli military carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks .
the Israeli attacks damaged or destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza area and about 250,000 people sought refuge in more than 100 UN schools rebuilt into preliminary shelters .
while tens of thousands of people continue to live in shelters and keep fighting , education authorities postponed the start of the school year last week .
&quot; I hope the school is open again soon so we can continue to learn , just like the children in the world and the Jewish children , &quot; said Mohammad Amara , a 13 @-@ year @-@ old boy who currently lives in a school in Gaza City .
