House prices have seen the strongest winter rise in seven years , a widely watched index shows .
the RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic Home Value Index for homes in the Australian capital rose 1.1 percent in August , according to RP data released Monday .
as a result of this increase , the overall increase in June , July and August is 4.2 percent , the largest increase in winter months since 2007 .
the annual price rise was 10.9 percent , more than double the increase in the 12 months to August 2013 , but the increases were not evenly spread across the country .
RP Data &apos;s research director , Tim Lawless , said Sydney and Melbourne are driving a two @-@ way market .
figures from RP Data show that house prices rose 16.1 per cent in Sydney last year , while in Melbourne , by 11.7 per cent .
the following markets are Adelaide , Brisbane and Darwin , in which prices rose on average by five and six per cent .
at the other end of the scale is Canberra , which has been hit hard by cuts in government spending and where prices rose only 1.4 per cent over the year .
Mr Lawless said further that with spring starting now for the next few months , an increase in properties for sale would be observed , which would subject the market to &quot; a real test . &quot;
&quot; if you look at the persistently high rate of auction prices , a generally fast sales rate and the persistently low interest rate , it is likely that home prices will rise further over the next three months , &quot; he said .
