Constantine Weckers ruthlessly honest memoir
it &apos;s actually more philosophical testimony than biography , which Constantin Wecker , Liedermacher , pacifist , politlessly activist , ex @-@ detainee , put on paper in &quot; monk and warriors &quot; on 287 pages .
not chronologically , but more mindsets for mind fences , the Munich @-@ born on June 1 , 1947 , wrote his memoir , each chapter initiated by a matching song text .
and he is ruthlessly honest : from onset to high school to shoplifting and drug use , he leaves no human weakness .
also , to show how he himself learned tolerance in dealing with his fellow men .
broad space also takes abstract but all the more important terms : love , soul , ego , being in the now , spirituality - all of which he tries to go to the bottom , in very philosophical but also very personal ways .
and he also explains his pacifism , his social critique , his political commitment - and also , as has shaped him not only the music ( the opera lover became a soul and rock musician ) , but also his prison stay .
the latter has also brought the Lebemann Konstantin Wecker closer to the asketic monk , which is &quot; created by subtraction , &quot; he says , &quot; by leaving everything unnecessary . &quot;
there are also short anecdotes between all the high mental views : about thugs in a locale frequented by GIs , or a crazy car ride , at which he visited a tree frontal .
here too , he is ruthlessly honest .
lenny Henry : my father never took me into the arm .
has never said &apos; I love you &apos;
Henry was one of seven children of a family of Jamaican immigrants in Dudley in the Midlands in 1958 .
his father , who died when Henry was 19 , worked in a factory and her relationship was limited .
