get away !
I want to watch cricket .
my older brothers Seymour and Hilton - who had already grown up when I was a child - went to the pub with him and talked about things , such as the shape of beer lashing or the beauty of a cricket strike .
I never had such a conversation with him .
much of my life he was this serious guy in the corner who read the newspaper .
Henry recently opened a foundry in Dudley , and although conditions are better than at times of his father , he won a glimpse of how life had been for him .
it &apos;s a little brighter now , but they &apos;re dark , smoked , deep stymied labyrinth with flames and smoke and lots of soot .
my father used to just put himself in the tub and then you could slowly hear him sing as he began to sing because he could wash the foundry of himself .
when I ran around there , it became clear to me that he had done this for years to bring food on the table , and my respect for it became greater .
yet Henry grew up as a child without love certificates from his parents .
my father never embraced me , he never said &quot; I love you . &quot;
only when my mother went bad towards the end of her life did we start saying , &quot; I love you , I love you , I love you . &quot;
