Kenya registers officials to curb &apos; ghost words&apos;
Kenya has begun registering all state officials biometric to erase &quot; ghosts &quot; from the government &apos;s payrolls .
employees who do not register in the next two weeks would no longer be paid , a government statement said .
the government suspects that thousands of people are still receiving salary payments even after their departure from the public service .
President Uhuru Kenyatta promised to fight corruption in public service when he took office in 2013 .
at an audit earlier this year , it was found that at least $ 1 million ( £ 700,000 ) per month was lost in payments for &quot; ghosts &quot; and by other abusive financial practices .
the government suspects that salaries will continue to be paid out in accounts after a person has died or leaves the public service , Wanyama Chebusiri reports for the BBC from the capital Nairobi .
all officials now have to appear at identification centers in the next two weeks to ensure their data on biometric registrations is recorded in a government statement .
all those who would not do so without a credible apology would be removed from the payroll , the communication went on .
&quot; this approach will contribute significantly to the rationalisation of the public service by identifying the actual number of officials and also by reassuring the payroll on both levels of government - so will the &quot; ghosts , &quot; said Anne Waiguru , the cabinet secretary at the Ministry of decentralisation and Planning .
