Berkeley declares housing market back for &apos; normal &apos;
one of London &apos;s most prominent builders pointed out that the housing market in the south @-@ east of England had &quot; returned to normal levels . &quot;
homes in the capital were hotly coveted and subject to huge price increases , prompting the Bank of England to set limits on mortgage lending in June because of widespread fears of a credit bubble .
Tony Pidgley , founder and chief executive of the highly @-@ rated construction company Berkeley said Monday : &quot; since the start of the current financial year , the market has returned to normal transaction levels since the peak of 2013 , &quot; adding that this provides a &quot; stable hand environment . &quot;
the property market in London was well positioned during the downturn as foreign buyers pushed into the capital .
according to information from the Qatar Office , prices in the city area rose by 18.5 per cent last year alone , far more than the average increase in England and Wales overall .
average sales prices at Berkeley &apos;s private , inexpensive and student offerings rose by about a fifth last year and were up by £ 423,000 at the end of April .
however , a stronger pound has made property ownership in London less attractive to foreign buyers in recent months - some of them have also been deterred by the introduction of new property taxes and political rhetoric about a possible &quot; residential tax &quot; ahead of next May &apos;s general election .
London real estate broker Foxtons warned last week that the mortgage market report for April , which unveiled tougher lending arrangements , would also lead to lower market growth in both property sales and prices in the second half of the year .
new data from the Bank of England Monday show a decline in mortgage approval in July , which also suggests that the property market is cooling .
Hamptions International , another real estate agency , corrected its forecast for the rise in property prices in London for 2015 down to 3 per cent , based on an already debilitating house price awareness .
transaction volume in the most expensive areas of London such as Chelsea , Mayfair and Kensington has now fallen by a quarter year on year , according to broker WA Ellis .
still , the desire for a home in the capital for Berkeley is a blessing , as the due amounts for futures sales amount to more than £ 2.2 billion .
Mr Pidgley added : &quot; demand for the right , well @-@ planned product at the best locations remained stable and as a result , futures sales have also remained stable . &quot;
in June , the company reported that it had sold 3,742 new homes in the year to the end of April - nearly a third more than the peak in 2007 before the crisis .
annual pre @-@ tax profit rose 40 percent annually to £ 280 million , sales up 18 percent to £ 1.6 billion .
in a statement Monday before the company &apos;s annual meeting , Mr Pidgley said that revenue for Berkeley in the current year was expected to match current market expectations .
analysts estimate the annual pre @-@ tax profit to be £ 450 million .
Berkeley shares were fixed at £ 23.96 in London trading in the afternoon .
