eurozone manufacturing at a 13 @-@ month low
the rise in output in the eurozone slowed to the lowest point of the past 13 months in August , according to a closely watched study .
the final Markit purchasing managers &apos; index of manufacturing ( PMI ) fell to 50.7 in August , according to a stand of 51.8 in July .
an indication above 50 indicates an expansion .
new orders declined and factories experienced breakthroughs at a time of rising tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine .
the figures meet before the European Central Bank ( ECB ) meeting on Thursday .
markets expect the bank to have a clear plan for dealing with a sluggish eurozone recovery , as well as for looming deflation at an inflation rate of just 0.3 % .
there is speculation that the head of the ECB , Mario Draghi , could provide further information later this week on whether to consider quantitative relief for the eurozone , according to those made by Britain and the US during the financial crisis .
&quot; although small growth is better than no growth at all , the slowing effects of increasing economic and geopolitical uncertainties have become clearer for manufacturers , &quot; said Rob Dobson , senior economist at Markit .
the factory PMI for Germany , Russia &apos;s largest trading partner in the EU , fell to its lowest level in 11 months , with 51.4 .
meanwhile , in the bloc &apos;s second @-@ largest economic nation , France , the PMI fell to 46.9 .
France remains a sorority , as well as Italy &apos;s descent from solid expansion to stagnation .
hints that growth incentives in key industrial markets will no longer affect Germany , Spain and the Netherlands are also not reassuring , &quot; said Mr Dobson .
the decline in industry probably fueled the fire of analysts who expect further monetary or fiscal stimulus .
positive news came from the Republic of Ireland , where the PMI rose to 57.3 , the highest level since the end of 1999 .
Howard Archer , chief economic expert at IHS Global Insight , said : &quot; the best thing to say for the purchasing managers &apos; index of manufacturing in the euro zone in August is that after that , the sector continues to grow . &quot;
he added : &quot; producers in the eurozone currently find life quite difficult , as current heightened geopolitical tensions - particularly with regard to Russia and Ukraine - are increasing uncertainty in the still difficult conditions in many countries .
these heightened uncertainties have clearly affected the economy - particularly , and consumer confidence , and presumably lead to some orders being delayed or even cancelled , especially large orders .
he said that it was &quot; increasingly likely &quot; that the ECB would eventually have to initiate some kind of QE &quot; although we suspect this will be limited . &quot;
