4 tips for better underwater photos and videos
if you like to take photos or videos underwater , there is a selection of devices .
the cheapest option is a waterproof point @-@ and @-@ shoot , like the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action Cam like the GoPro Hero3 + Silver Edition , both of which are available for about $ 300 .
I took these photos at a family festival with several cameras , all available at a price of under $ 350 .
regardless of the equipment , there are a few rules for the best results .
check your equipment twice .
even if you have a waterproof camera , make sure that the battery compartment and other subjects are close .
place your camera on the photos or videos you want to take .
some cameras and camcorder have scene and recording modes that optimize exposure time for the temperate underwater conditions .
and before you jump in , check to what depth your equipment is functional .
some cameras are only allowed for up to 5 feet , others up to 50 or 60 feet .
in our purchasing guide , search for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models .
make multiple shots - because many won &apos;t fold .
point @-@ and @-@ shoot cameras have an LCD with which you can compose images , action cams normally do not .
even if you have an LCD , it is difficult to see this underwater , and the right image setting is a good thing .
so make a lot of shots .
if your camera has a row mode that makes a series of shots with slightly changed exposure settings , use it .
stay close to the surface .
the light becomes dramatically worse , the further you move away from the surface .
so , if possible , stay close to the surface when you make shots in a pool , lake or sea .
this allows you to add more color to your photos ; the deeper you go , the less color you will see .
go close to the objects .
this is also a good advice on land , but it is all the more important under water because of poor light conditions .
it is particularly important when you work with an action cam : these devices often have a fixed wide @-@ angle lens , which means that you have to come to your objects more tightly if they are to fill out the entire picture frame .
Andrew Lawson was a man of the sort whose character changes things , even in such a gigantic organization as the NHS .
as a consultant anesthesiologist , he devoted his career to saving the sick both the agony of the disease and the anesthesia of treatment .
among his patients , his wife recalls , was an MI6 employee who had to live with the devastating effects of torture .
Lawson knew doctors were important to diagnoses and diseases , while the treated were mostly busy with something very different : pain .
one day in 2007 , however , he was the one whose suffering started .
&quot; I didn &apos;t feel like that , &quot; he wrote in May this year .
I had trouble getting up .
while he struggled with the flu @-@ like symptoms , he noted that he made impatient allegations to his wife Juliet .
&quot; I want everything right now rather than later , &quot; he noted .
when Juliet was on a business trip for a week , Lawson felt quite unusual and uneasy .
something was in the air .
he asked a colleague to conduct an X @-@ ray examination of his chest .
only two weeks ago he had been skiing in the French Alps .
the results of the X @-@ ray investigation were available .
he suffered from mesothelioma , an incurable cancer that attacks the chest , that is , the lungs of exaggerating skin .
as with most cancers , the exact trigger is usually difficult to determine .
for example , while some smokers are diagnosed with lung cancer , not all lung cancer patients have previously been smokers .
but Mesotheliom is different .
in almost all cases , the trigger is an asbestos load - contact with the fibre , which was once considered to be a &quot; miracle substance &quot; but has now been identified as deadly .
for most of us , Mesotheliom is a disease that can ignore how easily .
asbestos is , after all , a product of the past .
the most dangerous asbestos type has not been used in Britain since the 1960s , when industry volunteered to stop using it .
even where he was still used , only people in certain industries worked directly with the fabric - plumbers , construction workers , room workers and shipyard workers , for example .
as an industrial hazard from another time , it seems to be hardly worrying today .
but this complacency is inappropriate .
Britain , it seems , is experiencing the peak of a mesolthelioma today .
there are more deaths from mesothelioma here than in any other country in the world .
with a total of 2,500 deaths a year , twice as many people die from this disease than from road accidents .
annual figures of mesothelioma deaths since 1980 and likely future deaths in Britain
the reason we are seeing the deadly effects now , although asbestos has been illegal for years ( all asbestos types were banned in 1999 ) is that a mesothelioma is only developing after decades .
and the scourge of the mesothelioma is not limited to former workers of the construction industry .
asbestos was , and is often still , present in the houses where we live , the offices where we work , the schools where we learn and the shops where we shop .
and therefore Mesotheliom knows no class barriers , financial limits , professions or age .
the privileged bastions , from the elegant department stores in London to private schools , are not a shelter .
Parliament buildings are amply contaminated .
even in hospitals where we are supposed to be healthy , this deadly carcinogens have already been used as a starting point .
Andrew Lawson was not old .
he wasn &apos;t a plumber either .
it actually fell hard for him to imagine where he might have been in contact with asbestos .
then he found it out .
&quot; it looks like there was a lot of asbestos in the tunnels at Guy &apos;s Hospital , where I graduated for six years , &quot; he wrote .
all - students , nurses , doctors and Pförtner - use the tunnels .
you wonder how many of my peers will suffer from the same disease ?
unfortunately , he was able to answer that question in part .
&quot; of the four doctors trained at Guy &apos;s Hospital , and who have contracted Mesotheliom in the last five years , &quot; he wrote in a letter in 2010 , &quot; I &apos;m the last to live . &quot;
how many of us will get sick ?
at Andrew Lawson , Mesotheliom was diagnosed at age 48 .
when he died on February 17 this year , he was 55 .
this was an unusually long survival period .
fifty percent of all knife victims die within 8 months of diagnosis .
the disease always ends deadly .
so we can only repeat Lawson &apos;s question : &quot; how many of us will get sick ? &quot;
the UK &apos;s leading expert on mesothelioma , Professor Julian Peto , notes that between 1870 and 2050 , when the asbestos premium in Britain is expected to be stalled , a total of 90,000 of the disease will have fallen victim .
most of them have no idea at the moment that they will die like this .
an asbestos mine in Quebec , Canada Alamy
a short look at the files of the courts to which those concerned frequently turn for damages claims shows how far the scourge of the mesothelioma has already spread .
in June this year , Marks &amp; Spencer admitted , for example , that Janice Allen was negligently exposed to asbestos .
she worked for the chain for nine years , from 1978 to 1987 and was responsible for the clothing department at two locations - one of which was the flagship store on Oxford Street .
Mrs. Allen was only 18 years ago when she began her work at M &amp; S .
now she has two children in the twenties .
&quot; before this thing , &quot; she says , &quot; I had never heard of Mesotheliom , I didn &apos;t really know anything about asbestos yet .
I never thought that would affect me .
there are few people who know a lot about asbestos .
the fact is that the term asbestos refers not to a substance but to a group of six minerals .
the name stems from the word &quot; Asemform , &quot; a description of the fibre structure that makes the substance resistant and flexible .
three of the six were used in construction .
Chrysotil , also known as white asbestos , is now by far the most commonly found asbestos in buildings .
it was used for roof plates , floor panels , pipe isolations , boiler insulation , even for brake blades in cars .
it is less deadly than other forms of asbestos , but it is still seen by the EU and WHO as a &quot; major health risk &quot; with possible death .
however , the brown asbestos and blue asbestos ( Krokydolith ) are more dangerous .
Britain was once the world &apos;s largest importer of brown asbestos , and experts suspect that &quot; there is clear but indirect evidence that this was a main reason for the uniquely high mesothelioma rates . &quot;
an employee of Marks &amp; Spencer was suspended at the flagship store in Oxford Street , London , Asbest
Janice Allen may not have seen himself as a typical knife victim , but Julian Peto &apos;s work suggests that her story is by no means unusual .
he has presented a study by those affected , which shows that &quot; a significant proportion of mesothelioma without known suspension was probably caused by work or in the home by asbestos contact in the environment . &quot;
most of these contacts are based on the &quot; normal use and aging &quot; of our buildings .
it looks like no one can assume to be safe .
a report by Goddard Consulting , which examined Westminster &apos;s palace , shows how people might have been unwittingly exposed to the substance even in the heart of the government .
in 2009 , Goddard reported that service forces and pipe lines were contaminated behind Parliament &apos;s committee rooms with asbestos , whose deadly fibers could be upset by something as benign as &quot; strong air movements . &quot;
MPs are often accused of caring for their own interests , but here it looks like the opposite .
while the board of the Parliamentary Labor Service insisted that the Westminster Palace had received a &quot; clean health certificate , &quot; it is now undisputed that £ 1 billion of work needs to be raised over several years to renovate parliament , modernize electric installations and remove asbestos , and that after the general elections , MPs are more likely to meet in nearby 2015 .
the Goddard report also pointed out that &quot; the presence of asbestos has not been handled in accordance with the respective provisions . &quot;
no one can know if this mismanagement will cost lives .
all you can do now is wait .
one person who could never accurately determine contact with asbestos is Graham Abbott , a general health practitioner .
like Andrew Lawson , 50 @-@ year @-@ old Abbott suspects he was exposed to asbestos during his work in hospitals .
&quot; I worked in a hospital where asbestos lawsuits were positively decided , &quot; he says , &quot; but I can &apos;t prove it in my case .
it &apos;s so difficult to remember all the places where you &apos;ve worked , and the data .
what he remember is the day in early December 2009 , when he got such a fever .
he was 45 , and performed an operation just late in the evening .
suddenly I had shaking frost .
it came quite suddenly .
I felt terrible .
I believed the drive home no longer created .
as a doctor , Mr Abbott knew that the pain from the chest , the skin around his lungs was sticking .
but like Janice Allen , he had no reason to suspect a mesothelioma .
he didn &apos;t go to work a month .
