only now does he mean the scale of the epidemic .
&quot; it turned out that asbestos was very widespread , especially in large public buildings where pipes were often isolated with asbestos , &quot; he says .
the people exposed to asbestos in these buildings are now contracting .
and so Mesotheliom now meets younger people who have not worked in the typical professions .
the most dangerous pipes with asphyxiation in hospitals were beneath the earth , so patients probably were not exposed to the substance .
but many employees who switched from one building to another in pedestrian tunnels ( such as Andrew Lawson ) or in underground canteens ( as Graham Abbott often did ) came in contact with the toxic substances .
it turns out that over several decades after the war , hospitals may have been life @-@ saving for patients , but life @-@ threatening for treatment doctors .
it will still be removed today .
students placed their bunk burgers on asbestos mats .
and it doesn &apos;t just affect hospitals .
asbestos has often been used in offices , shops , libraries and city halls because of its fabulous insulating and flammable properties .
schools too .
in fact , many people probably had the first asbestos contact in the classroom .
across the country , in thousands of chemical dogs , students have put their bunch burgers on asbestos mats .
the issue of asbestos in schools is now frequently raised on websites .
and meanwhile , such innocent items have included asbestos in our homes as floor plates or wheelchairs by default .
&quot; it &apos;s an industrial product that is contained in large parts of our properties , &quot; notes Andrew Morgan , the lawyer who represented Andrew Lawson in his trial against Guy &apos;s Hospital .
in one case , the only contact that occurred to a affected woman was the demolition of a garden shed in the 1970s .
so adjust how to tear down your garden shed .
the effects of diagnosis , and the knowledge that the disease is incurable , is immense .
&quot; it takes a while to process that , &quot; says Graham Abbott .
I went back to work and tried to continue , but I realised I couldn &apos;t focus on what I was doing .
I was in practice for two weeks .
then I knew I had to go and take care of myself .
well , I won &apos;t see another Christmas .
with the greatest difficulty was the change of perspective from a doctor &apos;s position to that of a patient .
like countless patients before him , he recalls how overwhelmed he was by all the information he had to deal with .
&quot; it was very hard to absorb all of this , &quot; he says .
