and you gave me about 12 months .
I remember thinking , &quot; Well , I &apos;m not going to experience another Christmas .
it was then . &quot;
mesothelioma is particularly insidious because it is our life @-@ saving mechanism - breathing itself - that causes deadly cancer .
most cases of mesothelioma are caused by asbestos contact .
asbestos consists of smallest fibres .
if the asbestos are woven up and the fibres are inhaled , they can be found in the chest , the skin around the lungs .
asbestos fibres irritate the chest and can trigger cell mutations .
&quot; the problem arises with the inhaled needle @-@ shaped asbestos fibres , &quot; according to Professor Tom Treasure , a heart Thorax doctor who moved to Guy &apos;s Hospital in 2001 .
exactly the hospital from which Andrew Lawson suspects that it has exposed him to asbestos is now ironically , a leading centre in the treatment of mesothelioma .
Treasure knew Lawson and treated some others , who were probably also exposed to asbestos during their training in hospital .
once asbestos needles reach lung tissue , Treasure says , &quot; they are pressed from breathing to the edge where the skin is .
it is invasive from the very beginning .
the usual options for other cancers don &apos;t work so well at Mesotheliom .
for example , the effectiveness of an operation is hotly disputed .
some think she &apos;s worth a try .
Treasure denied that .
&quot; you can &apos;t cut off the chest , &quot; he says .
they don &apos;t get around with the knife .
meanwhile , the cancer &quot; does not speak very well on chemotherapy , &quot; which shows &quot; effect &quot; but does not heal .
&quot; sometimes there are long @-@ term survivors , &quot; Treasure says .
but in the end they all die .
fortunately , some patients actually live long , much longer than expected .
author Stephen Jay Gould died 20 years after diagnosis .
two and a half years after his own diagnosis , Graham Abbott is still fighting .
after he contacted Mesotheliom , Abbott came into contact with Andrew Lawson , who had become a one @-@ man support and consulting firm for co @-@ workers four years after his diagnosis .
&quot; hello , cancer center , &quot; he happily presented himself in calls .
&quot; he was very positive , &quot; Abbott says .
he had received his diagnosis 4 years earlier and was still very active .
initially , Abbott was offered six chemotherapy cycles , which would last four months and would likely extend his life by just one month .
&quot; I was desperate , &quot; he says .
