&quot; we had an advantage by not having to go further , I just called and got an appointment , &quot; Graham admits .
a normal patient would have to receive a transfer and wait for the authorisation of treatment .
money is crucial for mesothelioma sufferers to perform the best available therapies .
but if these treatments inevitably fail , many people face another financial worry - about the future of the families they leave behind .
and so they turn to the courts in the hope of compensation .
Andrew Lawson contacted Andrew Morgan of Field Fisher Waterhouse LLP .
&quot; it has been known since 1898 that asbestos is extremely dangerous to health , &quot; says Morgan .
but what changed in the 1960s was that one realized that a very low burden also posed a health risk .
and here business negligence began to play a role .
Andrew Lawson and Guy &apos;s Hospital eventually settled their case , but it was not what Morgan called a &quot; full @-@ fledged compensation , &quot; since Lawson could not prove with absolute certainty that his mesothelioma was due to an asbestos contact at Guy &apos;s .
however , following the investigation into his death , a spokesman for the Guy &apos;s confirmed that &quot; asbestos fibres were removed in the affected cellar area in the 1990s . &quot;
that was too late for Andrew Lawson .
how asbestos can be removed
indeed , for Mesotheliom sufferers seeking compensation , it is an enormous problem to assign the fatal asbestos contact of a company or a job - usually decades after the incidents .
many of their previous employers have been sold or closed .
insurance records can be lost .
and those who oppose claims know that the time is for them , but certainly not with the plaintiffs .
in response , there have been clear new legislation this year that makes it easier for Mesotheliom stakeholders to file compensation , even if their former employers are no longer found .
the law has set up a fund of £ 350 million funded by the insurance industry for anyone diagnosed after July 2012 , but cannot sue anyone .
in these cases , plaintiffs receive 80 per cent of what a court could have told them in a normal compensation process - about £ 120,000 .
about 300 successful applications at the program are expected each year .
Andrew Morgan , like so many Mesotheliom stakeholders , thinks that £ 350 million was a &quot; very good job &quot; of the insurance industry .
&quot; this is a deal by insurers for insurers , &quot; he says , suggesting that this amount is a quarter of what insurers would have to pay if time hadn &apos;t gone over and mesothelioma sufferers could find the companies and sue them normally .
Mike Penning , then @-@ Labor and retirement minister , also admitted that the law was &quot; not perfect . &quot;
but both Penning and Morgan admitted that , given seven deaths daily , rapid action is needed .
&quot; people are suffering so much and need help today , &quot; Penning said during the second hearing of the Mesothelioma Act in December last year .
at that time , Graham Abbott had been in the hands of Prof. Loic Lang @-@ Lazdunski for 19 months .
after their first deliberations , Lang @-@ Lazdunski recommended an operation from which he expects a positive effect , unlike Tom Treasure .
this was accompanied by radiotherapy and chemotherapy - a triple therapy with which Lang @-@ Lazdunski can present a survival rate of up to 40 percent over five years .
Abbott felt stronger .
&quot; this is obviously with the most important thing , &quot; Abbott says .
this is always seen in patients .
there is something that lets you continue .
when you give up , you get worse very quickly .
Graham Abbott underwent surgery in March 2012 .
