China denies Hong Kong right to rule , protesters swear retaliation
on Sunday , despite the increased calls for democratic reforms against the nomination of candidates for the 2017 elections by the Hong Kong electorate .
that approach probably fueled the long @-@ announced protests in Hong Kong &apos;s business district , while activists launched planning and mobilization within hours of the announcement .
the Chinese People &apos;s Congress &apos;s decision basically allows Communist leaders to reject all non @-@ peking candidates .
&quot; this is not unexpected , but it makes us angry , &quot; said legal expert Emily Lau , chairman of the Democratic Party .
that &apos;s not what Beijing had promised .
the inhabitants of Hong Kong have been blamed .
and it is clear that we are dealing with an authoritarian regime .
in his defense of the Chinese decision , Li Fei , vice @-@ general secretary of the Standing Committee of the National People &apos;s Congress , said that allowing public nominations in the elections would be too &quot; chaotic . &quot;
since 1997 , when Britain gave back control of Hong Kong to the Chinese , Beijing has promised to allow residents to choose the government seat from 2017 .
China &apos;s leaders presented Sunday &apos;s decision as a democratic breakthrough because it gives Hong Kong &apos;s citizens a direct electoral right , but the decision also makes it clear that China &apos;s leaders remain firmly in hand with a nominating committee closely controlled by Beijing .
a new clause also allows only candidates &quot; with love for the country and love for Hong Kong . &quot;
the decision follows a summer in which some of the largest and most publicized protests took place in Hong Kong for several years .
behind the pro @-@ democracy campaign in Hong Kong is the Occupy Central With Love and Peace movement , whose organizers have threatened to cut off the financial district if Beijing does not allow real general suffrage .
on Sunday night , within hours of the announcement , hundreds of Occupy Central supporters gathered in the rain ahead of Hong Kong &apos;s government headquarters .
at the demonstration , organizers said their movement had reached a new level of civilian disobedience and planned them protest waves in the coming weeks .
however , they did not elaborate on this , apparently in order to avoid problems with the authorities .
in an online communication , organizers announced that the movement &quot; considered the occupation of the Central District only as a last resort , an action to be taken only if all the dialogue opportunities are exhausted and there is no other choice .
we are sorry to say that all the opportunities for dialogue have been exhausted today and that the occupation of the Central District will definitely take place .
Hong Kong authorities have been preparing for Beijing &apos;s announcement for days , and it balked at tightening security measures including police forces and barricades on Sunday in front of the government building .
the unrest is amplified by the sense of many in Hong Kong that they are slowly losing control of their city .
the access of people from the mainland increases competition for products and services .
there is also a growing fear that Hong Kong &apos;s values like democracy and freedom of speech are beginning to crumble under Beijing &apos;s growing pressure .
some criticized the demonstrations of the Occupy Central movement as it threatens business operations - Hong Kong &apos;s lifeline .
