feminists criticize racial issue and police behaviour after Ferguson
the unarmed teenager was killed by a police officer in Ferguson , Mo.
participants raised their hands in the air and sang , &quot; hands high , not shooting &quot; while waiting before the funeral .
after two weeks of protests in Ferguson , Mo . , because of the shooting of unarmed teenager Michael Brown , the blogger Miriam Zoila Perez noticed a change in the online discussions of white feminists .
according to their experience , white feminist commentators put gender before the race when it comes to raising reproductive rights and income inequality .
however , while tensions in the Midwest rose and received attention across the country , Perez saw that white women &apos;s responses turned 100 % around the race .
compared with the responses of black women shortly after the shots of August 9 , personal essays with titles such as &quot; thoughts on Ferguson from a white woman &quot; and &quot; feminism isn &apos;t just about suppressing women &quot; relatively late .
but for Perez , that meant an important change .
&quot; I don &apos;t think you find in feminism a lot of people who are talking about white and privileges in such a high @-@ class way , &quot; she said .
people felt urged to express something about the incidents .
it is characteristic of the crisis in which we find ourselves and because the situation in Ferguson is so ethnized that they must express it .
for English professor Koritha Mitchell of Ohio State University , Ferguson brought problems to light to which black Americans are exposed every day , but who are not considered a &quot; women &apos;s beating &quot; in cultural space .
&quot; I can publish something funny on Facebook about me and my partner and get 150 likes from anywhere , &quot; Mitchell said .
if I post something about how Farmer is under siege in her own country , silence is deafening .
&quot; how can it be safe for women to talk publicly about a relationship , but not about security in public space ? &quot; she asked .
for black women like Mitchell , who have studied race , gender and sexuality in U.S. history , there is no dichotomy between racial and gender problems .
for them , black women have not had the luxury of separating the issues neatly ; they live in combined reality every day .
while white women now combine the themes of race and gender in feminist mainstream circles , Angela Hattery , professor of women and gender research at George Mason University , says their predecessors were doing the opposite .
&quot; between 1865 and 1890 , at least 10,000 black men were yelled and the rationale was almost always the rape of a white woman , &quot; Hattery said .
white women had to be involved in the story to justify the lynching .
for Hattery , the split between white and black women came at the point where white combatants for women &apos;s voting rights such as Susan B. Anthony analyzed the country in the late years of the 19th century and determined that the fight for voting rights could only be successful for one group : women or blacks .
&quot; they made the decision to stand up for women &apos;s vote , and the right to vote for blacks should come later , &quot; Hattery said .
recalling such things , one realises with power why coloured women don &apos;t trust white women .
we didn &apos;t do our job well .
we never helped black women protect their husbands and sons .
even after women were given the right to vote in 1920 , it lasted a decade before white women organized themselves against the lynch in the Association of Southern Woman for the Prevention of Lynching .
the group emerged nearly 40 years after the original request for help from pages of black women , Mitchell says .
for Mitchell , the tide of white feminist reactions to questions raised by Ferguson - police behavior , racial discrimination - is a mirror of the time when white feminists played &quot; fliers &quot; with the problems that black women have faced for generations .
&quot; wouldn &apos;t it be great if the activists who have such traditional feminist platforms approach a child &apos;s right to education as seriously as they do with the right to contraception ? &quot; asked Mitchell .
second @-@ generation feminists who built up their careers on the battle for reproductive rights and access to contraceptive means are now trying to understand what that means .
well @-@ known white feminist activist Gloria Steiner went on Facebook two weeks after the shooting of Michael Brown and released a pointy article from Rebecca Carroll , columnist of the Guardian , in which she calls for more protests from white Americans on racism .
&quot; I hope that women who have another but parallel reason to understand a danger inherent to the body - and opinions on race that are significantly different in public polls - will cite the changes , &quot; Steiner wrote .
although Steiner stands for a more intersectional feminism in which racial and gender issues are addressed , some of her comments on the racial issue in America are stunned .
Christina Sommers , a researcher at the American Enterprise Institute and author of &quot; Who Stole Feminism ? &quot; said to She The People that young men in the United States , especially young coloured men , are &quot; far more vulnerable than their sisters , &quot; but Steinem &apos;s remarks to Ferguson are contrary to their previous criticism .
there are now hundreds of special programs for girls and young women , but almost nothing for boys .
but when the White House recently launched a small program , My Brother &apos;s Keeper , to help vulnerable young black and Hispanic men , there were annoying reactions from many feminists , including Gloria Steiner .
the relationship between police and the black community is not the only problem pushing into the forefront of mainstream feminism .
after the U.S. border police picked up nearly 63,000 unaccompanied minors on the country &apos;s southwest border this year , the issue of immigration reform is also returning to the surface - this time as a women &apos;s theme .
Andrea Mercado , co @-@ chair of We Belong Together , an organization that mobilizes women for immigration reform , said that for a reconsideration of the issue as a key women &apos;s theme , they simply had to publish the stories of immigrant women .
&quot; these speak for themselves , &quot; Mercado said .
when the vast majority of working visas go to male immigrants , the women who accompany them are in a position where they are vulnerable to domestic violence and exploitation .
&quot; these stories find an afterthought in the women &apos;s organizations , &quot; she said .
