Ebola : the epidemic strains West Africa &apos;s economy
the Ebola epidemic in West Africa is also a serious blow to the economy .
markets are orphaned - and international companies are at a distance .
the devastating Ebola epidemic is a serious blow to West Africa &apos;s economy .
the harvest rotates in the fields , the mines are left and the markets are wasting - the virus has been hard on the region .
some international companies are already at a distance .
&quot; the Ebola epidemic is not only a medical crisis but also an economic one , &quot; the head of the African Development Bank , Donald Kaberuka , ruled .
Liberia is hardest hit
&quot; it &apos;s a total disaster , we &apos;re losing a lot of money , &quot; says Alhaji Bamogo , who sells clothes in the second @-@ largest market in Liberia &apos;s capital , Monrovia .
on the market comes just who wants to buy food or something for disinfection against Ebola .
Liberia has been hit hardest by the virus , where more than 600 people fell victim to the fever alone .
recently , health officials said the disease had penetrated at every angle of the country .
the virus has also spread in Guinea , Sierra Leone and Nigeria .
in total , more than 1500 people have died , and thousands more have died .
foreign firms pull employees off
companies throughout the resource @-@ rich countries suspend their operations .
foreign companies such as the Arcelor Mittal steel company withdraw their employees , several international airlines no longer fly the affected regions .
local traders and farmers are also reacting : few merchants are still leaving their homes in order to recover .
in some areas in Sierra Leone and Liberia , which are under quarantine , among other things , the cocoa and coffee beans that are important for export in the fields .
farmers do not dare to leave their homes for the harvest .
food is scarce
&quot; people are going to travel less and less , &quot; says Phillipe De Vreyer , Paris expert on the economy of West Africa .
the man , for example , who normally goes to the market and sells his vegetables , prefers to stay at home .
the population therefore receives the consequences of the epidemic directly and urgently : food is scarce .
in the markets , the stockpile of staple foods such as rice is dwindling .
at the same time , the region heavily dependent on international firms is threatening to have an image , with far @-@ reaching consequences .
the biggest danger is that international firms are generally long @-@ running the area , says Philippe Hugon of French think tank Iris .
what is crucial is how far and how long the virus will spread .
investors may feel that it is dangerous to live and thus invest in Guinea , Sierra Leone and Liberia , &quot; Mr Hugon warns .
the disease also charges states &apos; strained state budgets
the disease also affects the already strained state budgets of the states concerned .
the ratings agency Moody &apos;s is concerned that its budgets are heavily strained by high spending on the health system and in addition by the deteriorating economy .
the African Development Bank has already promised to help the health systems of the affected countries with $ 60 million ( $ 45 million ) .
the effects are also noticeable in Nigeria , where so far few Ebola cases have been diagnosed .
although the oil @-@ rich region in southern Nigerdelta has not yet been affected .
but elsewhere , many people already remain at home for fear of contagion .
reservations in hotels also go back significantly .
