genetic disorder often misdiagnosed
a Britin says she thought as a result of a misdiagnosis over many years that she would die .
Karin Rodgers lived almost her entire youth in the belief that she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease .
she actually suffered from the Charcot @-@ Marie @-@ Tooth disease ( CMT ) - a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spinal cord .
charity CMT UK announced that misdiagnosis is a frequent problem in people with CMT because so little is known about this disease .
about 23,000 people in Britain probably suffer from CMT , which can lead to motor disruptions such as muscle weakness , an uncertain gear and cracked toes .
the disease is incurable and progressing , which means that symptoms get worse with time .
when Rodgers was 13 , she believed she was suffering from Friedreich @-@ Ataxie ( FA ) - a disease with very poor chances of survival .
Rodgers thought she would sit in a wheelchair before she &apos;d 18 , and die before her 30th birthday .
the mother of two children , now 51 years old , said : &quot; as a child I knew I couldn &apos;t do the same as the others .
I fell constantly and everything lasted longer with me .
I could never ride with the other children wheelchair or skateboard and was often hired in school because of my way and running .
Rodgers said she looked at her medical records at the age of 13 after several operations to relieve her Achilles and stretching her feet when her doctor had left the room and read that she was suffering from FA .
&quot; I felt guilty because I had been curious , so I didn &apos;t tell anyone , but I went home , searched for the disease in the library and wrote to the FA society , &quot; she said .
when I received an answer , I was shocked and terribly panicked .
I thought I &apos;d be in a wheelchair with 18 and die with 25 , and in between slowly losing all my skills .
I did all this alone with me and planned my own funeral .
she said when she became 17 , she became clear that her skills had not diminished as much as she had imagined and asked her doctor .
he just stood up , and hugged me and said , &quot; My love , I don &apos;t think you have that , otherwise you &apos;re already warming up in a wheelchair now . &quot;
I think you have a little less life @-@ threatening .
after some genetic tests , her CMT was found .
&quot; when he explained to me what CMT was like I felt like I was a winner , &quot; she said .
charity CMT UK has launched a CMT Award @-@ winning month to draw attention to this disease .
