tax burden on businessmen in Washington area rises with economic recovery
a recovery in the economy means more customers , more sales and new jobs .
it also means higher taxes .
government and local tax rulings for companies in the country rose slightly last year , while the economic recovery accelerated , according to a newly published study last week , and firms in the Washington area formed no exception .
companies in the Area District , Maryland and Virginia jointly paid $ 27.6 billion to state and local authorities in the 2013 financial year , an increase of 3.8 percent compared with 2012 revenue of $ 26.6 billion .
the company &apos;s government and local tax burden rose 4.3 per cent to $ 671 billion last year , compared to 3.9 per cent the year before , and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of falling modesty in 2009 and 2010 .
government taxes rose more than local levies , up 4.3 percent , according to the study conducted by the services agency Ernst &amp; Young with the Center for State Taxation , a tax policy group .
more than half of the District &apos;s tax revenue , 56 percent , comes from corporate taxes , while 36 percent of Marylands &apos;s revenue comes from businesses .
Virginia achieves the lowest tax revenue from companies with 28 percent .
much of the increase in tax revenues is grounded in a recovery in the company &apos;s property values , researchers say , leading to an increase in property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after the three consecutive years with growth rates of less than 1 percent .
while much of these gains came from large states such as California , New York and Texas , the course also seems to be reaching for the Washington area .
companies in the District , Maryland and Virginia jointly paid more than $ 10 billion to state and local real estate agents last year , compared to $ 9.6 billion in 2012 - an increase of 4.2 percent over a year .
but the apparent recovery in property values is not as effective in Maryland in raising government and local tax revenues , as property taxes here amount to just over a fifth of companies &apos; tax bills .
companies in Virginia and D.C. pay nearly half of their state and local taxes in the form of property taxes .
&quot; in Maryland , a large part of the real estate , especially in the tax area around D.C. , is either owned by the government or by non @-@ profit organizations that don &apos;t pay property taxes , &quot; said Douglas Lindholm , managing director of the Center on State Taxation .
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes , for example , to provide the same services that other states offer .
the recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovery of the real estate market
company revenues also appear to be recovering , according to the data .
companies in the region reported income taxes at state organizations of $ 2.3 billion compared to 2.1 billion in 2012 .
Maryland took $ 1 billion in corporate income taxes , the region &apos;s highest amount .
while the trend is heading in the same direction , the local tax burden on businesses does not rise evenly in all three places .
the entry rate in the District was 4.3 percent of the national average , while the rise in Maryland was significantly higher , 4.9 percent .
only Virginia reported below @-@ average tax revenue of 4.1 percent .
Virginia , with 6 percent in all three jurisdictions , has significantly the lowest corporate income tax rate ( in all three , there are fixed corporate tax rates ) .
Maryland &apos;s corporate tax rate is 8.25 percent and in the District at relatively high 9.975 percent .
a similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that fewer state and local corporate taxes are required in Virginia and overall there is a better tax rate than in Maryland .
the study did not examine the District .
despite the benefits , Virginia is under pressure from its southern neighbor .
North Carolina has passed laws to reduce its corporate tax rates this year from 6.9 per cent to 6 per cent , the same rate as Virginia , and the rate will fall to 5 per cent next year .
if the state continues to meet its income targets next year , this law could reduce the state &apos;s corporate income tax rate to 3 percent by 2017 .
meanwhile , small businesses in the Washington area seem to be doing better , and they therefore pay more state and local taxes , according to the latest study .
corporate taxes paid as personal income taxes by small businessmen - a transitional structure under which most small businesses are organized - in the District , Maryland and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $ 2.4 billion , a marked faster rate of growth than corporate taxes overall .
researchers say the trend and increase in corporate taxes across the country is likely to continue this year , with an increase in overall multi @-@ party tax revenue for the state and local governments rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year .
still , the Washington area could lag behind if the federal government &apos;s spending cuts affect the region &apos;s labor market .
