Amazon buys Twitch for $ 1.04 billion
Amazon just confirmed what information had reported Monday morning : the online retailer - and video maker , and a variety of other things - is buying the video streamlining service Twitch for $ 1.04 billion ( $ 970 million ) .
the announcement comes as a surprise , not because no one expected a takeover of Twitch , but because it was widely suspected that YouTube would acquire the company .
three months ago , it looked as though the sale of Twitch to Google &apos;s video service was decided for a cool billion , and the collaboration also seemed natural .
twitch , founded only three years ago as Justin.tv , was launched as a general streaming service - a live version of YouTube .
instead , it quickly became a platform for players who wanted to publish their bragging pieces in games , a &quot; YouTube for live games , &quot; according to an insider .
the Twitch interface .
and &quot; let &apos;s play , &quot; a video genre in which better the ( mostly older ) games give a hint of secrecy theaters , are already very popular on YouTube .
it &apos;s just that YouTube is often called when you want to describe Twitch , so the news that YouTube wanted to buy Twitch was somewhat bored , a textbook example of an established technology company buying up a potential competitor .
it &apos;s a mystery of why the deal with YouTube didn &apos;t come about , as the company reportedly agreed to pay as much as Amazon .
all we know at the moment is this statement by Emmet Shear , president of Twitch : &quot; we chose Amazon because they believe in our community , they share our values and long @-@ term visions and they want to help us get there faster . &quot;
another secret is , frankly , the incredible success of Twitch .
for Snobs like me , who explain that they prefer sport rather than watching it , it is hard to understand the attraction that emanates from watching others while playing , rather than taking the control console into their own hands .
it &apos;s one thing to look at a friend at 3 a.m. over the shoulder while she &apos;s snapped by resident Evil , and something completely different , to watch a spinner as he is shot 20 times in Call of Duty in the head .
you could just watch all these games now .
another problem is that many of the most popular games are now ego games , so the addition without its own control over the eye perspective can be a really good recipe for headaches .
I admit that the quick runs in which the Roger Bannisters of our electronics age complete games are entertaining .
but until a game or humor virtuoso is involved , his Twitch channel is probably not so interesting .
but what do skeptics like me know about it ?
twitch is called by 55 million different visitors per month and is the fourth largest source of Internet traffic tips .
and how exactly does Amazon want to make money out of it ?
it &apos;s hard to imagine Twitch being so elegantly integrated into Amazon Instant Video as YouTube Twitch could easily have swallowed .
but Twitch has something every company would like to see : thousands of young men encircled as advertisers .
as the chairman of Twitch , Shear said , Amazon and Twitch &quot; believe both in the future of gaming , &quot; and the medium shows no signs of contraction , not even - sip - as spectator sport .
